0
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:26,870
Oh, my God, it's the baby!

2
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:32,716
Are you all right?

3
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:37,795
I'm frightfully sorry.
It appears you've missed your bus.

4
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:07,797
I'm terribly sorry, I--

5
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:16,554
-Missed your bus.
-I don't own a bus.

6
00:05:16,720 --> 00:05:18,039
I'll buy you one.

7
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:21,033
How nice, a rich Yank. No, thank you.

8
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:24,272
If you don't want a bus,
how about some coffee?

9
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:26,874
I don't drink coffee.

10
00:05:27,400 --> 00:05:29,038
I drink tea.

11
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:32,875
There probably won't be a bus
along here for some time.

12
00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:35,554
Probably not.

13
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:53,395
You really drink this, don't you?

14
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:58,315
No, we just like to pour it into cups
and stir it. Why did you ask?

15
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:02,837
-It tastes too much like boiled water.
-It is boiled water.

16
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,831
I knew there was a reason.

17
00:06:10,320 --> 00:06:13,437
-Where are you from?
-Chicago.

18
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:17,389
-Where gangsters come from.
-Some come from Detroit.

19
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:20,313
-Chicago grows the best.
-You a gangster?

20
00:06:20,520 --> 00:06:23,637
Twelve arrests, no convictions.

21
00:06:26,240 --> 00:06:30,074
-Nobody looks like that in a uniform.
-How should I look?

22
00:06:30,320 --> 00:06:34,393
-Like a short man.
-Your boiled water's getting cold.

23
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:39,552
Then let's order some more.

24
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:42,795
Please.

25
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:46,676
All right.

26
00:06:57,760 --> 00:07:01,435
-What about you?
-What about "what about me?"

27
00:07:01,600 --> 00:07:04,433
Who are you? What are you?

28
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:10,709
I'm a short man, born in London.
I've lived here all my life.

29
00:07:10,880 --> 00:07:14,668
-What do you do here?
-I work in a hospital.

30
00:07:14,960 --> 00:07:18,748
I tell men they'll be all right
and they believe me...

31
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:20,831
...because they want to.

32
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,677
Then I watch them die.
I want it to all end.

33
00:07:28,120 --> 00:07:33,717
-I'll win the war for you.
-That would be nice.

34
00:07:36,400 --> 00:07:40,029
-Are you stationed here?
-Our base is an hour from here.

35
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:43,556
-I get a day every couple of weeks.
-You're a pilot?

36
00:07:43,720 --> 00:07:45,199
B-25s.

37
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:48,716
-Do you like to fly?
-I hate to walk.

38
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:54,079
-My name's Halloran, what's yours?
-Tell me about America.

39
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:57,357
-I think you're lovely.
-Tell me about Chicago.

40
00:07:57,520 --> 00:08:00,353
Chicago's windy.
Something's happening here.

41
00:08:00,520 --> 00:08:03,114
-Please don't.
-Please don't what?

42
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:06,192
-I have to go.
-I don't want you to go.

43
00:08:06,360 --> 00:08:09,796
-I shouldn't be here.
-Yes, you should.

44
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:12,955
I have to go.

45
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,594
-I have to catch the bus.
-Don't leave.

46
00:08:19,760 --> 00:08:22,194
-I want to see you again.
-You can't.

47
00:08:22,360 --> 00:08:28,196
-Look, I just have a few hours.
-Please don't do this to me.

48
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:32,069
-We've got to get into a shelter.
-I'm sorry, I can't--

49
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:34,231
Why?

50
00:10:58,520 --> 00:11:02,399
You're trying to go away again,
but I'm not gonna let you.

51
00:11:02,600 --> 00:11:04,795
I'm not gonna let you.

52
00:11:04,960 --> 00:11:08,919
-I can't think. I have to go home now.
-I'll take you there.

53
00:11:09,080 --> 00:11:12,755
No, you can't.
I have to go.

54
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:17,630
My name's David Halloran,
I'm from Chicago. I won't let you go.

55
00:11:17,880 --> 00:11:20,872
-Tell me your name.
-I'm sorry.

56
00:11:21,040 --> 00:11:24,510
-You won't tell me your name?
-Please let me go.

57
00:11:24,680 --> 00:11:28,798
I have to see you again.
My next day off is in two weeks.

58
00:11:29,280 --> 00:11:31,714
-I can't.
-Meet me here Thursday.

59
00:11:31,880 --> 00:11:35,190
-No!
-On the same corner. Right here.

60
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:38,875
-I won't be here.
-I will, I'll be here all day.

61
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:42,954
-Please don't, I won't come.
-I'll be here.

62
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:47,875
We can't act like nothing's happened.
There's not enough time.

63
00:11:56,480 --> 00:11:57,879
It's too late.

64
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:29,957
The objective this morning
is this airfield north of Rouen.

65
00:12:30,120 --> 00:12:33,829
Reconnaissance showed
we didn't do too well last night.

66
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:37,993
These dark circles here
are fuel storage tanks.

67
00:12:38,160 --> 00:12:44,076
They're under concrete, so it'll take
more than one hit to knock them out.

68
00:12:44,240 --> 00:12:48,518
Again, recon photos show
they didn't take even one direct hit.

69
00:12:48,680 --> 00:12:50,591
We'll approach from the east.

70
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:55,036
We'll have the sun at our backs
and in their eyes.

71
00:12:55,200 --> 00:13:00,149
How come he says "we"?
He's not going. We're we.

72
00:13:00,720 --> 00:13:04,838
We expect light to moderate flak.
We'll approach from 12,000.

73
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:10,233
Cloud cover at 6 to 8000.
We'll drop at 6000.

74
00:13:10,400 --> 00:13:15,428
-I wish I were going with you.
-We'll stay, you can go.

75
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:18,672
Lt. Halloran?
Something you want to say?

76
00:13:18,920 --> 00:13:22,708
I'm sure no one wants to miss
whatever you have to add.

77
00:13:22,960 --> 00:13:24,632
Yes, sir, what?

78
00:13:25,320 --> 00:13:30,075
No one wants to miss anything,
except I don't have anything to add.

79
00:13:30,240 --> 00:13:34,233
So there's nothing
for any of us to miss, sir.

80
00:13:39,360 --> 00:13:42,591
Takeoff is at 0800.
Good luck, gentlemen.

81
00:13:51,920 --> 00:13:57,119
-What is " light to moderate flak"?
-Less than heavy flak.

82
00:13:57,280 --> 00:14:02,877
-It's more than no flak.
-He wishes he could go with us.

83
00:14:03,040 --> 00:14:06,077
Somebody's got to stay behind
to volunteer us.

84
00:14:15,560 --> 00:14:16,549
Radio check.

85
00:14:16,760 --> 00:14:18,796
<i>Pilot to tail, okay?</i>

86
00:14:18,960 --> 00:14:22,475
<i>Everything's fine, sir.</i>
<i>Radio's okay, ammo's okay.</i>

87
00:14:22,640 --> 00:14:25,791
<i>Radio check, pilot to waist.</i>
<i>Giler?</i>

88
00:14:25,960 --> 00:14:27,518
<i>-Yes, sir?</i>
<i>-How we doing?</i>

89
00:14:27,680 --> 00:14:30,717
<i>All set, sir.</i>
<i>Radio's okay, ammo's okay.</i>

90
00:14:30,880 --> 00:14:33,269
<i>Radio check, pilot to turret. Lucas?</i>

91
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:37,991
<i>Yes, sir. Ready, sir.</i>
<i>Ammo's okay, radio's okay.</i>

92
00:14:39,080 --> 00:14:42,834
<i>Bomb bay closed?</i>
<i>Flaps locked.</i>

93
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:45,355
<i>Cimino?</i>

94
00:14:45,520 --> 00:14:50,355
<i>I don't understand. They make it</i>
<i>so hard to get in these things.</i>

95
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:54,308
<i>I don't even want to be here</i>
<i>in the first place.</i>

96
00:14:56,320 --> 00:15:02,031
<i>I understand making it hard to</i>
<i>get out, everybody wants to get out.</i>

97
00:15:02,760 --> 00:15:07,959
<i>These things are made of metal.</i>
<i>Ever try to pick one up? You can't.</i>

98
00:15:08,120 --> 00:15:14,036
<i>You know why? Because it's made of</i>
<i>metal and metal's heavy, very heavy.</i>

99
00:15:14,200 --> 00:15:17,351
<i>Don't believe me?</i>
<i>Just try and pick one up.</i>

100
00:15:17,520 --> 00:15:21,718
<i>You'll see. You'll wrench your back,</i>
<i>that's what you'll do.</i>

101
00:15:21,880 --> 00:15:26,795
<i>Air isn't heavy, you know?</i>
<i>This pile of junk is heavy.</i>

102
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:30,316
<i>Heavier than air. Much heavier.</i>

103
00:15:30,480 --> 00:15:36,112
<i>Don't you see? This thing</i>
<i>is not supposed to be up in the air.</i>

104
00:15:36,680 --> 00:15:40,355
<i>Jesus, I hate these things.</i>

105
00:15:44,040 --> 00:15:48,670
<i>We're 20 miles from target,</i>
<i>descending, bombs away at 6000.</i>

106
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:53,069
Roger, Pacer Leader.
Descending to 6000.

107
00:15:53,600 --> 00:15:57,912
<i>This is leader. Maintain positions,</i>
<i>we are 12 miles from target.</i>

108
00:15:58,080 --> 00:16:01,959
<i>Rate of descent, 1000 feet per minute.</i>

109
00:16:03,120 --> 00:16:04,951
They're shooting guns at us.

110
00:16:08,320 --> 00:16:12,836
Somebody forgot to tell the Germans
they should only have light flak.

111
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:14,069
<i>Bomb bay open.</i>

112
00:16:16,840 --> 00:16:18,637
<i>Seven miles to target.</i>

113
00:16:24,160 --> 00:16:26,435
Feather it.

114
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:36,549
-It's feathered.
-Let's turn back.

115
00:16:37,120 --> 00:16:40,032
-How far from target?
<i>-Five miles. Turn back!</i>

116
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:42,395
-He's right.
-Have to slow to 200.

117
00:16:42,560 --> 00:16:46,155
-We'll be sitting ducks.
-We'll get our asses shot off!

118
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:49,198
<i>How far from target?</i>

119
00:16:49,360 --> 00:16:52,033
Three miles. Am I the only one
who's not crazy?

120
00:16:52,280 --> 00:16:54,236
Ever take a look at Hyer?

121
00:16:54,480 --> 00:16:58,871
<i>If there's a God, he doesn't send Hyer</i>
<i>to prep school and Yale...</i>

122
00:16:59,120 --> 00:17:03,272
...to let him die in a plane.
So as long as we're with him...

123
00:17:03,520 --> 00:17:06,034
<i>... the Krauts can't get at us.</i>

124
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:10,830
I'm messy enough to take Hyer down
with me! We're over the target.

125
00:17:11,080 --> 00:17:14,629
<i>I'm gonna drop the bombs</i>
<i>and let's get out of here!</i>

126
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:15,789
Just a second.

127
00:17:16,040 --> 00:17:19,077
We're over it,
the engine's falling off!

128
00:17:19,640 --> 00:17:24,589
-Chief, what do you think?
-It'll hold, if you wanna wait.

129
00:17:24,760 --> 00:17:29,993
Terrific, we've got Sergeant York
on the plane. I hate you, Lucas!

130
00:17:30,160 --> 00:17:34,233
We're over the goddamn target,
let me drop the bombs.

131
00:17:34,400 --> 00:17:36,231
We're over the target!

132
00:17:36,480 --> 00:17:40,598
You're early because
you're afraid the wing will fall off.

133
00:17:40,760 --> 00:17:45,834
-I'm gonna wait a few more seconds.
-I hate Lt. David Halloran!

134
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,231
-Serial number 057327--
-969.

135
00:17:49,400 --> 00:17:51,550
Let him drop the bombs!

136
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:56,191
<i>If we don't hit the target now,</i>
<i>we'll have to come back again.</i>

137
00:17:56,360 --> 00:18:00,273
-Now we're really over the target!
-Well, drop the bombs!

138
00:18:03,560 --> 00:18:05,869
<i>They're away.</i>

139
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,390
<i>Jesus, I hate these things.</i>

140
00:20:54,440 --> 00:20:59,560
I was there on Hanover Street
for over an hour, just watching you.

141
00:20:59,720 --> 00:21:04,555
-I was afraid, so I stayed hidden.
-Are you still afraid?

142
00:21:04,720 --> 00:21:11,068
Yes. I wasn't a few minutes ago,
when we had something to do...

143
00:21:11,240 --> 00:21:14,596
...but now I just feel awkward again.

144
00:21:15,040 --> 00:21:19,238
-I don't know what I'm doing here.
-Yes, you do.

145
00:21:19,400 --> 00:21:21,994
Yes, I do.

146
00:21:25,360 --> 00:21:30,798
-I'm not hungry anymore.
-Neither am I.

147
00:23:31,680 --> 00:23:36,276
Thursday. I can get back to London
next Thursday.

148
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:39,156
-Tell me your name.
-I can't.

149
00:23:39,320 --> 00:23:41,197
-Please?
-No.

150
00:23:41,360 --> 00:23:43,999
I'm frightened.
It's happening so fast.

151
00:23:44,440 --> 00:23:49,753
I'll bet your name is really Fred.
You're embarrassed.

152
00:23:52,840 --> 00:23:55,149
Hey, Fred...

153
00:23:56,320 --> 00:23:58,754
...I think I love you.

154
00:24:00,920 --> 00:24:03,229
Yes.

155
00:24:04,240 --> 00:24:08,472
<i>Leader to group, we are 20 miles</i>
<i>from target, begin your descent.</i>

156
00:24:08,640 --> 00:24:11,916
<i>-Bombs away at 8000 feet.</i>
<i>-10,000.</i>

157
00:24:13,040 --> 00:24:14,234
Open bomb bays.

158
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:17,029
<i>Bomb bays open.</i>

159
00:24:21,120 --> 00:24:25,796
They're shooting guns at us again.
How come they do that every time?

160
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:29,396
<i>-We drop bombs on them.</i>
-They have no sense of humour.

161
00:24:29,560 --> 00:24:31,118
Can't you take a joke?

162
00:24:31,560 --> 00:24:34,677
<i>-9000.</i>
<i>-Five miles to target.</i>

163
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:38,279
-How far is target now?
<i>-Three miles.</i>

164
00:24:38,440 --> 00:24:42,228
-Altitude?
-8500.

165
00:24:44,960 --> 00:24:46,951
We're almost over the target.

166
00:24:47,600 --> 00:24:51,832
-Altitude?
-8200.

167
00:24:52,160 --> 00:24:55,516
-8100.
-Cimino, drop them!

168
00:24:55,760 --> 00:24:58,354
<i>They're away.</i>
<i>Halloran, I love you!</i>

169
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:02,634
There really is a God,
ladies and gentlemen.

170
00:25:02,800 --> 00:25:05,189
I'm going to church
when we get back.

171
00:25:05,440 --> 00:25:10,036
<i>So I haven't been in a while,</i>
<i>I missed a few Sundays.</i>

172
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:18,312
What's a cross between
a parakeet and a tiger?

173
00:25:18,520 --> 00:25:22,069
-I give up. What?
-I don't know, but if he sings, listen.

174
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:25,392
You think that's funny?
You're a wretched child.

175
00:25:25,560 --> 00:25:28,233
-lf I am, it's your fault.
-Really? Why?

176
00:25:28,400 --> 00:25:32,313
Mrs. Thomas said children
are a reflection of their parents.

177
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:37,349
-But Dennis doesn't have a moustache.
-He's a reflection of his mother.

178
00:25:37,600 --> 00:25:40,956
Dennis calls his parents by their
names. It's smashing.

179
00:25:41,120 --> 00:25:42,235
Really?

180
00:25:42,440 --> 00:25:45,989
I'm too old to keep on calling you
Mummy and Daddy.

181
00:25:46,160 --> 00:25:51,109
-You only call me Daddy, not Mummy.
-I think I shall call you Paul.

182
00:25:51,280 --> 00:25:54,590
-lf that's what you'd like.
-Yes, Paul.

183
00:25:54,760 --> 00:25:59,117
-And I shall call you Margaret.
-And I'll call you Rover.

184
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:04,150
-No, I'll call you Mummy.
-For a short person, you're not bad.

185
00:26:04,360 --> 00:26:06,078
-More tea?
-I'd love some.

186
00:26:06,400 --> 00:26:10,393
Judy Fox stole my keychain,
you know the one with the clover?

187
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:12,357
-Stole it?
-Yes.

188
00:26:12,600 --> 00:26:14,033
How do you know?

189
00:26:14,240 --> 00:26:17,710
I brought it to school.
I was changing after gym...

190
00:26:17,920 --> 00:26:20,718
...and I couldn't find it. She had it.

191
00:26:20,920 --> 00:26:25,835
When I said it was mine she said she'd
always had it.

192
00:26:26,040 --> 00:26:28,315
And I know it's mine.

193
00:26:28,520 --> 00:26:31,830
Everyone has to be nice,
because her father died.

194
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:35,276
-When did he die?
-A few months ago, in Africa.

195
00:26:35,440 --> 00:26:40,560
She says it's hers. It isn't. I'm glad
you're intelligent. You won't die.

196
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:45,794
I'm in Intelligence. And you should be
especially kind to her now.

197
00:26:45,960 --> 00:26:49,350
-You won't die, will you, Daddy?
-Wasn't it Paul?

198
00:26:49,520 --> 00:26:52,990
Promise me.
And you will always love me?

199
00:26:53,240 --> 00:26:57,153
-I'll always love you.
-And you'll always love Mummy?

200
00:26:57,320 --> 00:26:59,470
-Even when you're 80?
-Yes.

201
00:26:59,640 --> 00:27:03,838
I'll have to put my false teeth in
to kiss her.

202
00:27:13,080 --> 00:27:16,117
-We're going back to Rouen.
-I'm gonna be sick.

203
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:20,751
We believe the Krauts are sending
an ammunition train south.

204
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:23,355
They'll expect us.
It won't be easy.

205
00:27:23,960 --> 00:27:26,713
-You'll get lots of flak.
-Definitely sick.

206
00:27:26,960 --> 00:27:29,679
Halloran, you fly lead.
Packman, second.

207
00:27:29,920 --> 00:27:35,119
You've got cloud cover from 8 to
10,000. Make the drop at 6000.

208
00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:38,317
I know what it's gonna be like,
so be careful.

209
00:27:38,480 --> 00:27:43,634
He flew 100 missions over Texas
and he knows what it's gonna be like.

210
00:27:43,880 --> 00:27:47,714
We should have 5- to 10-mile
visibility below 8000.

211
00:27:47,880 --> 00:27:50,030
Approach from south to north.

212
00:27:50,280 --> 00:27:54,193
Nobody ever took Texas
while he was there.

213
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:59,039
Takeoff is at 0830.

214
00:27:59,200 --> 00:28:05,389
Good luck. I wish I could've gone
with you. Dismissed.

215
00:28:06,960 --> 00:28:11,112
Lt. Halloran, I'd like
to speak with you for a moment.

216
00:28:13,440 --> 00:28:17,877
Take it easy with him. Don't say
anything you'll regret later.

217
00:28:18,240 --> 00:28:23,792
Don't take it easy. Say something
you'll regret, maybe we'll be grounded.

218
00:28:26,320 --> 00:28:28,276
Sit down, lieutenant.

219
00:28:30,120 --> 00:28:35,990
In every group of men, there's
