Captain, I heard it!

445
00:47:34,400 --> 00:47:36,960
-I thought we were gonna play?
-No.

446
00:47:37,200 --> 00:47:39,760
Believe me, Packman!

447
00:47:39,960 --> 00:47:41,916
I heard it, Packman!

448
00:47:42,880 --> 00:47:45,872
Goddamn you, Packman!

449
00:49:03,360 --> 00:49:05,316
Please don't smoke.

450
00:49:13,800 --> 00:49:16,189
Lieutenant Wells...

451
00:49:16,440 --> 00:49:19,671
...English is a language
you do not understand.

452
00:49:19,880 --> 00:49:22,474
You have never spoken a word.

453
00:49:22,680 --> 00:49:26,195
They didn't teach you
English in Essen.

454
00:49:26,400 --> 00:49:29,756
You must never speak in English
or respond to it...

455
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:33,959
...even around here, no matter what.
If it's in English...

456
00:49:34,160 --> 00:49:38,995
...you do not understand. Even if
it's the PM himself talking to you.

457
00:49:39,200 --> 00:49:42,954
One slip like that
and you're quite dead.

458
00:49:43,160 --> 00:49:47,517
All right, lesson over.
It's time we took a break.

459
00:49:48,240 --> 00:49:53,553
Don't be discouraged, you're doing
fine. Come on, I'll pay for the tea.

460
00:49:53,760 --> 00:49:57,389
Come on, it's all right.

461
00:49:57,600 --> 00:50:01,832
Lt. Wells, class is over
for the afternoon.

462
00:50:16,440 --> 00:50:20,035
Sometimes when we're together...

463
00:50:20,240 --> 00:50:25,109
...I feel so close that I don't know
where I end and you begin.

464
00:50:26,520 --> 00:50:29,910
I never knew it could be like that.

465
00:50:30,120 --> 00:50:34,432
I was 19 when I got married.
He was the only man I'd ever known.

466
00:50:35,840 --> 00:50:41,312
I never felt I lacked anything, it's
just I wasn't sure if this was it.

467
00:50:42,880 --> 00:50:48,830
If this was everything. Maybe that's
why I went with you that first day.

468
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:55,034
It's so damned unfair. I try
so hard to forget you, I really do.

469
00:50:55,760 --> 00:51:01,630
I spend all my time trying to forget
you, so I think of you all the time.

470
00:51:01,840 --> 00:51:05,116
I don't want to hurt anybody.

471
00:51:07,240 --> 00:51:12,872
Sometimes I sit at the dinner table
with him and I watch him...

472
00:51:13,080 --> 00:51:16,390
...and I want him so desperately
to do something...

473
00:51:16,600 --> 00:51:20,513
...or say something
or be something that I can hate.

474
00:51:21,240 --> 00:51:25,552
But he never does.
I've hurt him so much.

475
00:51:25,760 --> 00:51:29,719
It makes me hate myself
and wish I've never met you...

476
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:32,514
...but then when I'm with you...

477
00:51:33,240 --> 00:51:37,597
...and it's so strong and
I don't ever want to let you go.

478
00:51:40,200 --> 00:51:43,431
Why don't things work
the way they're supposed to?

479
00:51:43,640 --> 00:51:46,632
I don't know how
things are supposed to work.

480
00:51:46,840 --> 00:51:50,116
I don't know anymore
what I heard in that engine.

481
00:51:52,680 --> 00:51:57,913
Before, a propeller could have fallen
off and I wouldn't have gone back.

482
00:51:58,120 --> 00:52:02,113
It's easy to be brave when you haven't
got anything to lose.

483
00:52:02,360 --> 00:52:04,635
I'm scared now.

484
00:52:04,840 --> 00:52:07,638
I don't wanna die
and not see you anymore.

485
00:52:07,840 --> 00:52:12,709
Nothing makes sense until I'm with you,
then everything makes sense.

486
00:52:15,480 --> 00:52:19,837
I don't wanna let you go.
I wanna be with you all the time.

487
00:52:20,760 --> 00:52:24,673
I don't wanna wake up and not know
if I'll see you.

488
00:52:24,880 --> 00:52:27,155
I'm tired of missing you.

489
00:52:27,720 --> 00:52:31,156
I'm in pieces.
I want you to put me back together.

490
00:52:31,360 --> 00:52:35,911
Hold me now,
make everything outside go away.

491
00:52:36,800 --> 00:52:39,553
On my way in to see you...

492
00:52:39,760 --> 00:52:42,957
...I was trying to
think of a way to tell you...

493
00:52:43,160 --> 00:52:46,197
...we should stop seeing each other.

494
00:52:46,400 --> 00:52:49,198
I did the same thing.

495
00:52:50,920 --> 00:52:55,152
Here are your two main types:
your combination lock...

496
00:52:55,360 --> 00:52:58,909
...and your key lock.
With your combination lock...

497
00:52:59,120 --> 00:53:02,715
...which works with a series
of tumblers...

498
00:53:02,920 --> 00:53:07,675
...you have to find out whether it's
a three- or four-number combination.

499
00:53:07,880 --> 00:53:11,668
Then, whether you move
to the right or the left.

500
00:53:11,880 --> 00:53:16,158
If it's your key lock, it's
a matter of finding the proper key.

501
00:53:16,360 --> 00:53:20,035
In the absence of a key,
a common problem...

502
00:53:20,240 --> 00:53:24,358
...there are certain instruments
that do a right proper job.

503
00:53:24,560 --> 00:53:29,634
-It's a matter of learning to use them.
-How long will it take?

504
00:53:30,080 --> 00:53:36,110
You've got to understand, opening these
is not something any old bloke can do.

505
00:53:36,320 --> 00:53:41,348
-It's a gift, if I do say so myself.
-Let's say Lt. Wells is gifted.

506
00:53:41,560 --> 00:53:46,680
A key lock, a couple of days,
a combination lock, six months.

507
00:53:46,880 --> 00:53:52,193
-We're interested in a Cona 335.
-That's a Jerry safe.

508
00:53:52,400 --> 00:53:56,154
-We are at war with the Germans.
-You've got a point.

509
00:53:56,360 --> 00:53:59,272
-Which is it?
-It's a key lock.

510
00:53:59,480 --> 00:54:05,032
Any schoolkid could crack it. In fact,
I cracked one when I was a schoolkid.

511
00:54:05,240 --> 00:54:11,554
Right. Now, gentlemen, here you have,
before your very eyes, your lock pick.

512
00:54:11,760 --> 00:54:16,675
You have here your safe, which is
almost the same as your Cona 335.

513
00:54:16,880 --> 00:54:22,876
Insert your lock pick
into your Cona 335...

514
00:54:23,080 --> 00:54:26,516
...feeling your way
through the elements.

515
00:54:26,760 --> 00:54:30,309
For your information,
there happen to be four.

516
00:54:33,440 --> 00:54:35,829
One.

517
00:54:36,040 --> 00:54:40,158
Two. Three.

518
00:54:41,800 --> 00:54:43,518
Four.

519
00:54:49,920 --> 00:54:54,152
Apple pie. Bleeding apple pie.

520
00:54:59,360 --> 00:55:03,035
-Nice to see you, lieutenant.
-Nice to see you.

521
00:55:03,240 --> 00:55:05,959
Why don't you sit down?

522
00:55:09,360 --> 00:55:13,638
I have a little problem.
It's a special mission.

523
00:55:14,720 --> 00:55:18,156
The group said they needed a volunteer.

524
00:55:18,360 --> 00:55:22,239
It's risky, so they wanted
to put it on a voluntary basis.

525
00:55:22,440 --> 00:55:27,230
It's for tomorrow night.
Oh, about the other day...

526
00:55:27,440 --> 00:55:31,956
...the mechanic couldn't find
a thing wrong with that engine.

527
00:55:32,160 --> 00:55:38,599
If you felt there was something wrong,
I'm sure there was. If you heard it....

528
00:55:38,800 --> 00:55:44,397
A mechanic's not a pilot. I don't
listen to any kind of rumour. Never.

529
00:55:44,600 --> 00:55:47,319
There's been a lot of talk around.

530
00:55:48,040 --> 00:55:51,669
You can't pay any attention
to that kind of talk.

531
00:55:51,880 --> 00:55:57,591
I don't believe for a moment
that you made the whole thing up.

532
00:55:57,800 --> 00:56:02,555
Not a word. Just gossip.
Now, where was I?

533
00:56:02,760 --> 00:56:06,230
Oh, yeah. That mission tomorrow night.

534
00:56:06,440 --> 00:56:10,194
I knew that you'd want
to volunteer to do it.

535
00:56:10,400 --> 00:56:12,914
Not that you've
got anything to prove.

536
00:56:13,120 --> 00:56:17,955
I just felt that you'd like
to go for it.

537
00:56:18,200 --> 00:56:22,273
I told Operations to have
those engines double-checked.

538
00:56:22,480 --> 00:56:28,510
I'm sure you won't be disappointed
and have to cancel that flight.

539
00:56:30,800 --> 00:56:34,156
-Is he ready?
-As ready as he ever will be.

540
00:56:34,360 --> 00:56:35,554
What do you mean?

541
00:56:35,800 --> 00:56:40,794
I can't be too specific.
There's nothing wrong with Wells.

542
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:43,594
I'd prefer he was more spontaneous.

543
00:56:43,840 --> 00:56:47,150
-Spontaneous?
-He learns what he's taught.

544
00:56:47,360 --> 00:56:51,911
But I'm not sure how he'll react
if something unforeseen happens.

545
00:56:52,120 --> 00:56:56,113
-Prepare him for everything.
-That would be nice.

546
00:56:56,320 --> 00:57:00,518
New stuff, this.
Supposed to be a cooler smoke.

547
00:57:00,720 --> 00:57:04,030
We're not going to send Wells
on a regular flight.

548
00:57:04,280 --> 00:57:07,909
We have to be paranoid
about the leak in Intelligence.

549
00:57:08,120 --> 00:57:12,591
We're going to drop him
in a totally different way.

550
00:57:12,800 --> 00:57:17,510
If this is cool, I'd hate to think
what they call hot.

551
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:25,473
We won't use Intelligence. We won't
even use a transport aircraft.

552
00:57:25,680 --> 00:57:30,037
As a matter of fact, we're not
even using a British aircraft.

553
00:57:30,240 --> 00:57:34,119
Would you come with me
to that tobacconist?

554
00:58:06,560 --> 00:58:08,312
Hello, how have you been?

555
00:58:10,080 --> 00:58:12,719
-Hello, handsome.
-What's it today?

556
00:58:12,920 --> 00:58:15,115
I do hope you like potatoes.

557
00:58:19,120 --> 00:58:22,795
-Your dinner is served, my lord.
-I'll take it in the study.

558
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:25,912
Very good, my lord.

559
00:58:28,640 --> 00:58:30,949
-There's a call for you.
-Where?

560
00:58:31,160 --> 00:58:32,957
At the nurses station.

561
00:58:39,280 --> 00:58:40,998
Hello? Hello?

562
00:58:41,200 --> 00:58:43,998
I can't hear, it's madness here. Paul?

563
00:58:44,200 --> 00:58:47,192
Yes. Can you hear me now?

564
00:58:47,400 --> 00:58:50,949
-Better. You'll have to speak up.
<i>-Is this all right?</i>

565
00:58:51,160 --> 00:58:53,435
<i>-Is anything the matter?</i>
-No, no.

566
00:58:53,640 --> 00:58:59,033
I'm sorry if I disturbed you.
I just wanted to hear your voice.

567
00:58:59,240 --> 00:59:03,711
Of course you haven't disturbed me.
I'm glad to hear your voice too.

568
00:59:04,040 --> 00:59:05,917
I love you, Margaret.

569
00:59:07,080 --> 00:59:08,354
I love you too.

570
00:59:08,640 --> 00:59:12,553
-I know I'm not that special.
-Of course you're special.

571
00:59:12,760 --> 00:59:18,357
No, I'm not and we both know it.
It's just my curse to be so ordinary.

572
00:59:18,560 --> 00:59:21,916
I do so want to be dashing.

573
00:59:22,120 --> 00:59:25,396
<i>I can't blame you</i>
<i>for finding me unexciting.</i>

574
00:59:25,640 --> 00:59:30,873
Why are you talking like this?
You're very special. And dashing.

575
00:59:31,080 --> 00:59:33,548
<i>Mrs. Sellinger, ward 4.</i>

576
00:59:33,760 --> 00:59:37,070
<i>-I didn't mean to disturb you.</i>
-I'm glad you called.

577
00:59:37,280 --> 00:59:39,236
<i>Mrs. Sellinger, ward 4.</i>

578
00:59:39,440 --> 00:59:44,833
-I have to go, they're calling me.
-I understand. Talk to you later.

579
00:59:45,040 --> 00:59:47,759
-I love you.
<i>-Paul--</i>

580
01:00:22,320 --> 01:00:26,916
-<i>Yes, Captain Sellinger?</i>
-Could you get me Lt. Wells, please?

581
01:00:34,280 --> 01:00:37,238
<i>-Hey, it's dark out.</i>
<i>-No kidding?</i>

582
01:00:37,440 --> 01:00:39,351
<i>Really, I wouldn't fool you.</i>

583
01:00:39,600 --> 01:00:44,230
<i>-Why are we the only plane taking off?</i>
<i>-We got a special mission.</i>

584
01:00:45,480 --> 01:00:49,792
<i>Lucky us. When it's dark out,</i>
<i>you can bump into things.</i>

585
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:54,551
<i>-I'll be real careful.</i>
<i>-Hey, Cimino, where are the bombs?</i>

586
01:00:54,760 --> 01:00:57,479
<i>We're a bomber. We drop bombs.</i>

587
01:00:57,680 --> 01:01:02,959
<i>No bombs. I like that.</i>
<i>Bombs are dangerous, they can blow up.</i>

588
01:01:03,160 --> 01:01:08,280
<i>We're waiting for an English guy</i>
<i>named Wells. We're gonna drop him.</i>

589
01:01:08,480 --> 01:01:11,677
<i>I like that, dropping a person.</i>

590
01:01:11,880 --> 01:01:14,952
<i>People don't blow up like bombs.</i>

591
01:01:15,800 --> 01:01:18,678
<i>-Starting port engine.</i>
<i>-Starting port engine.</i>

592
01:01:29,280 --> 01:01:30,633
<i>How do they sound?</i>

593
01:01:30,840 --> 01:01:35,516
<i>They sound fine. Even if they don't</i>
<i>sound fine, they sound fine.</i>

594
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:41,393
<i>-Where the hell's that English guy?</i>
<i>-It's dark, maybe he's not so stupid.</i>

595
01:02:05,760 --> 01:02:09,196
-Is this Wells?
-There's been a change of some kind.

596
01:02:09,400 --> 01:02:12,039
Captain Sellinger, Lt. Halloran.

597
01:02:26,160 --> 01:02:27,388
Hello?

598
01:02:27,600 --> 01:02:30,558
-Mummy!
-Hello, darling.

599
01:02:31,360 --> 01:02:33,032
Your hair smells nice.

600
01:02:33,240 --> 01:02:36,471
-Mrs. Carling got soap in my eyes.
-Did you cry?

601
01:02:36,680 --> 01:02:40,355
Wouldn't you cry
if she got soap in your eyes?

602
01:02:40,560 --> 01:02:42,949
-Where's Daddy?
-He went out.

603
01:02:43,160 --> 01:02:47,711
-Mrs. Carling gave me dinner.
-Did he say where he was going?

604
01:02:47,920 --> 01:02:51,549
He left a note on the pillow.
I think that's romantic.

605
01:03:06,120 --> 01:03:10,079
What does Daddy say? Is it mushy?

606
01:03:11,960 --> 01:03:17,273
-Daddy has to go away on a little trip.
-When will he be back?

607
01:03:17,480 --> 01:03:21,393
-Very soon.
-Your coat's all wet.

608
01:03:21,560 --> 01:03:24,791
I did a painting of
a Tyrannosaurus Rex in orange.

609
01:03:24,960 --> 01:03:27,679
Have you ever seen an orange one?

610
01:03:27,880 --> 01:03:31,919
Come and look at it.
Mummy, come on!

611
01:03:36,720 --> 01:03:40,793
I don't mean to be pushy, but
that Englishman isn't English.

612
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:44,959
He's your actual Kraut.
You can tell by his collar.

613
01:03:45,160 --> 01:03:49,995
I forgot to tell you.
We're on the German side now.

614
01:03:50,200 --> 01:03:53,237
<i>-I like the uniforms.</i>
-Sellinger, are you okay?

615
01:03:53,480 --> 01:03:54,799
Quite well.

616
01:03:55,000 --> 01:03:57,958
We're over France.
We'll avoid the Germans.

617
01:03:58,160 --> 01:04:03,280
-This mission's not that crazy.
-We'll drop you through the hatch.

618
01:04:03,480 --> 01:04:06,517
<i>Keep your arms tight to your body.</i>

619
01:04:06,720 --> 01:04:09,154
I shall remember, thank you.

620
01:04:12,800 --> 01:04:15,030
Jesus Christ!

621
01:04:23,400 --> 01:04:25,595
How bad is it?

622
01:04:28,240 --> 01:04:33,792
No. It's a mistake.
You're not supposed to die.

623
01:04:36,280 --> 01:04:39,955
-It's all a mistake.
<i>-Lt. Halloran! Are you all right?</i>

624
01:04:40,160 --> 01:04:45,154
-We're hit up here. It's bad.
-I'm afraid we've been hit back here.

625
01:04:45,360 --> 01:04:47,715
<i>-How bad?</i>
-I think they're dead.

626
01:04:47,920 --> 01:04:51,833
Lucas? Giler? Cimino?

627
01:04:52,040 --> 01:04:53,519
Cimino!

628
01:05:01,960 --> 01:05:05,873
Cimino, don't do this.
Please don't--

629
01:05:13,240 --> 01:05:17,199
Oh, my God.
He has no face.

630
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:22,275
Your men back there...

631
01:05:23,160 --> 01:05:24,718
...they're dead.

632
01:05:26,840 --> 01:05:28,910
He has no face.

633
01:05:53,960 --> 01:05:58,715
Keep your arms tight!
Don't pull the ring till you're clear!

634
01:06:51,200 --> 01:06:56,911
It's like someone took a vacuum
cleaner and straightened out the mess.

635
01:06:58,480 --> 01:07:00,710
They're all gone.

636
01:07:02,680 --> 01:07:07,071
It's not right.
They should have left a mark.

637
01:07:07,280 --> 01:07:09,316
I'm really sorry.

638
01:07:11,200 --> 01:07:13,111
I know how you feel.

639
01:07:13,960 --> 01:07:18,590
-I'm so sorry I caused all this.
-It's not your fault.

640
01:07:19,200 --> 01:07:21,316
You know where we are?

641
01:07:22,120 --> 01:07:23,792
20 miles south of Lyon.

642
01:07:24,040 --> 01:07:27,316
Well, that's where I have to go.

643
01:07:27,480 --> 01:07:32,315
I gotta make my way to the Channel.
That's the other direction.

644
01:07:32,720 --> 01:07:37,316
-Good luck.
-Thank you. Thank you for everything.

645
01:07:40,080 --> 01:07:44,471
I beg your pardon, lieutenant.
Lyon is north of here, you say?

646
01:07:44,680 --> 01:07:46,750
Yeah. I'm pretty sure.

647
01:07:49,080 --> 01:07:52,629
I hate to impose,
but do you know which way is north?

648
01:07:52,840 --> 01:07:56,799
-Yeah, that way.
-Thank you again.

649
01:08:01,560 --> 01:08:04,199
Oh, damn!

650
01:08:04,400 --> 01:08:09,190
Lt. Halloran, I'm sorry
to be such a burden to you...

651
01:08:09,400 --> 01:08:12,119
...but would you mind giving me a hand?

652
01:08:23,840 --> 01:08:28,516
It's sprained, it'll be sore for
a while. Can I ask you a question?

653
01:08:28,680 --> 01:08:29,715
Sure.

654
01:08:29,960 --> 01:08:35,956
You don't seem to know north from south
and you fall on your ass immediately.

655
01:08:36,200 --> 01:08:39,112
-Have you ever done this before?
-No.

656
01:08:39,320 --> 01:08:43,598
Wonderful.
You look real spiffy in uniform.

657
01:08:44,840 --> 01:08:49,311
I don't want to go with you.
You don't know what you're doing.

658
01:08:49,520 --> 01:08:53,069
And I certainly
don't know what I'm doing.

659
01:08:53,280 --> 01:08:57,319
But here I am, as we speak,
going with you.

660
01:08:58,080 --> 01:09:01,914
-We'll get our asses shot off.
-I'm really grateful.

661
01:09:02,120 --> 01:09:04,714
That's just swell.

662
01:09:09,920 --> 01:09:11,069
Hello?

663
01:09:11,240 --> 01:09:13,879
<i>Mrs. Sellinger? This is Major Trumbo.</i>

664
01:09:14,080 --> 01:09:17,390
Oh, my God. It's Paul.
Is he all right?

665
01:09:17,600 --> 01:09:20,398
<i>The plane he was on was shot down.</i>

666
01:09:20,600 --> 01:09:26,436
I have no more information, but it's
possible he bailed out and he's fine.

667
01:09:26,640 --> 01:09:28,232
I just don't know now.

668
01:09:29,120 --> 01:09:31,315
<i>Mrs. Sellinger, are you there?</i>

669
01:09:31,840 --> 01:09:36,709
<i>As soon as I learn more, I'll call.</i>
<i>Your husband's a good man.</i>

670
01:09:36,920 --> 01:09:42,358
I'm sure he's fine, I just can't
understand why he replaced Wells.

671
01:09:42,560 --> 01:09:45,154
<i>Not like him to be so impulsive.</i>

672
01:09:45,360 --> 01:09:50,388
<i>I'll call you as soon as I learn</i>
<i>anything. I'm sure he's fine.</i>

673
01:09:50,600 --> 01:09:52,750
<i>Mrs. Sellinger, are you there?</i>

674
01:09:52,960 --> 01:09:54,712
Thank you.

675
01:09:56,040 --> 01:09:58,508
Thank you for calling.

676
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:24,675
Mummy, is everything all right?

677
01:10:30,080 --> 01:10:34,039
-How far do you think we've gone?
-You're the spy.

678
01:10:34,240 --> 01:10:37,755
-Don't you have a manual?
-Yes, we do.

679
01:10:37,960 --> 01:10:40,872
-Didn't you ever read it?
-I wrote it.

680
01:10:41,080 --> 01:10:44,436
-What does it say about distances?
-I forget.

681
01:10:44,640 --> 01:10:47,518
We're gonna get our asses shot off.

682
01:12:56,560 --> 01:13:01,509
Give me a hand, she's gonna kill me.
She thinks I'm German.

683
01:13:01,720 --> 01:13:05,395
I wonder why she thinks
you're German?

684
01:13:06,360 --> 01:13:09,989
Betty Grable, Hershey bars,
Yankee Stadium. Hello, Joe.

685
01:13:13,840 --> 01:13:17,310
She had a brother who was killed
by the Germans.

686
01:13:17,520 --> 01:13:22,548
Her father wouldn't do anything.
He's a collaborator. Out of fear.

687
01:13:22,760 --> 01:13:26,230
She says she's doing
what he should be doing.

688
01:13:28,200 --> 01:13:31,795
It's his car,
she says we can take it.

689
01:13:45,000 --> 01:13:48,117
-This will work out rather well.
-I'm thrilled.

690
01:13:48,320 --> 01:13:54,555
As an SS officer, I'm entitled to
an aide. You won't look out of place.

691
01:13:54,760 --> 01:13:59,311
-Where won't it look out of place?
-At Gestapo headquarters in Lyon.

692
01:14:00,440 --> 01:14:04,513
You've got a right to get killed,
I have a right to live.

693
01:14:04,720 --> 01:14:09,316
I appreciate your position, but
I don't think I can do this alone.

694
01:14:09,520 --> 01:14:13,433
My leg is hurt and this thing
is important.

695
01:14:13,640 --> 01:14:17,394
I don't speak German,
in case you didn't notice.

696
01:14:17,600 --> 01:14:22,674
If you don't speak to anyone,
no one will know. That makes sense.

697
01:14:22,880 --> 01:14:24,518
Shit.

698
01:15:11,280 --> 01:15:14,556
Get rid of the cigarettes.
And the lighter.

699
01:15:14,760 --> 01:15:16,716
They're American.

700
01:15:22,080 --> 01:15:25,277
-Do you mind if I ask you something?
-Not at all.

701
01:15:25,480 --> 01:15:29,109
Why did you decide to go
instead of Wells?

702
01:15:29,320 --> 01:15:32,756
That's complicated.
I don't know how to answer that.

703
01:15:32,960 --> 01:15:34,393
Try.

704
01:15:36,600 --> 01:15:41,469
All my life, no matter what I did,
I've always been the same thing.

705
01:15:41,680 --> 01:15:46,196
Pleasant. I'm pleasant. I was
a teacher, a pleasant profession.

706
01:15:46,400 --> 01:15:50,598
I'm pleasant-looking.
If anyone were to describe me...

707
01:15:50,800 --> 01:15:56,238
...they'd say I was pleasant.
I never minded it that much before.

708
01:15:56,440 --> 01:16:00,638
Except now it's beginning to hurt.

709
01:16:00,840 --> 01:16:04,116
-More than I thought it could.
-What do you mean?

710
01:16:04,320 --> 01:16:07,357
-Look at yourself.
-I can't, I'm driving.

711
01:16:07,560 --> 01:16:11,075
Take a good look
at yourself and you'll see a hero.

712
01:16:11,280 --> 01:16:13,111
I don't want to be a hero.

713
01:16:13,320 --> 01:16:19,714
You are one, you can't help it.
When the boy falls through the ice...

714
01:16:19,920 --> 01:16:24,630
...you save him. I'm the one who
gives you my coat to wrap him in.

715
01:16:24,840 --> 01:16:30,995
When it's all over, you're in the
paper, saying it was really nothing.

716
01:16:31,200 --> 01:16:32,997
And I have a wet coat.

717
01:17:15,960 --> 01:17:18,520
Are you kidding?

718
01:17:19,960 --> 01:17:23,032
You're supposed to
open the door for me.

719
01:19:40,920 --> 01:19:45,835
They've changed it.
They put in a combination safe.

720
01:19:46,040 --> 01:19:50,318
-I have no idea how to open it.
-I love it.

721
01:19:54,960 --> 01:20:00,318
-Mrs. Sellinger, what a surprise.
-I'm sorry to barge in like this.

722
01:20:00,520 --> 01:20:05,355
I haven't heard anything since
last night and I'm beside myself.

723
01:20:05,560 --> 01:20:09,633
-I was hoping you'd have news.
-Won't you sit down?

724
01:20:09,840 --> 01:20:11,717
Would you like some sherry?

725
01:20:11,920 --> 01:20:14,878
-Cigarette?
-What the hell happened?

726
01:20:16,440 --> 01:20:21,036
We don't know. The plane is missing.
Not a word. Not a trace.

727
01:20:21,240 --> 01:20:25,438
-I can't understand Paul's actions.
-I can.

728
01:20:25,640 --> 01:20:29,349
-Really, why?
-It's not something I can explain.

729
01:20:30,040 --> 01:20:33,874
I'll contact you
as soon as I hear anything.

730
01:20:34,080 --> 01:20:39,074
I spoke to the American colonel,
Bart, and they're waiting too.

731
01:20:39,280 --> 01:20:43,751
-Who's Colonel Bart?
-Paul was in an American plane.

732
01:20:43,960 --> 01:20:47,714
-Bart is the wing commander.
-Where's he located?

733
01:20:47,960 --> 01:20:51,873
-At Windsor Field.
-Thank you, major.

734
01:20:52,080 --> 01:20:56,471
-I'm sorry for pestering you.
-Seeing the colonel won't help.

735
01:20:56,680 --> 01:21:00,992
-He knows no more than I do.
-I'm sure you're right.

736
01:21:01,200 --> 01:21:04,158
Thank you again.

737
01:25:40,760 --> 01:25:43,718
Are you out of
your goddamn mind?

738
01:28:13,440 --> 01:28:15,874
-Mrs. Sellinger?
-Yes.

739
01:28:16,080 --> 01:28:18,469
I'm Colonel Bart.

740
01:28:18,680 --> 01:28:23,674
-It's nice of you to see me.
-Not at all. Will you sit down?

741
01:28:25,920 --> 01:28:30,357
You must think I'm a pest.
I have to know what's happened.

742
01:28:30,560 --> 01:28:35,031
Yes, of course. Well, we've received
no notification of survivors.

743
01:28:35,400 --> 01:28:37,391
Can't send reconnaissance in.

744
01:28:37,600 --> 01:28:41,149
We can't draw attention
to the mission, understand?

745
01:28:41,400 --> 01:28:42,549
No, I don't.

746
01:28:42,760 --> 01:28:48,153
-There's every chance they bailed.
-But you don't know for sure.

747
01:28:48,360 --> 01:28:53,957
No. But I do know that if they did,
your husband is in very good hands.

748
01:28:54,160 --> 01:28:59,712
The pilot, Lt. Halloran, is a very
determined, very resourceful man.

749
01:29:08,760 --> 01:29:09,954
Apple pie?

750
01:29:37,320 --> 01:29:39,311
We did it.

751
01:29:39,800 --> 01:29:42,519
We actually did it!

752
01:29:43,080 --> 01:29:48,074
-We're still not out of France.
-We'll get out, all right.

753
01:29:48,320 --> 01:29:52,108
It would be silly to have come
this far and not get out.

754
01:30:06,120 --> 01:30:11,478
I can go back now.
I can be more for her to see.

755
01:30:12,400 --> 01:30:14,834
-She must be very special.
-She is.

756
01:30:15,040 --> 01:30:17,998
Have you ever felt that way
about any woman?

757
01:30:18,200 --> 01:30:23,832
Yeah, I do now.
Except with me it's different.

758
01:30:24,080 --> 01:30:26,753
Since I met her,
I don't know who I am.

759
01:30:27,000 --> 01:30:30,834
I know who you are.
You're a good and brave man.

760
01:30:31,040 --> 01:30:32,758
I don't feel very brave.

761
01:30:33,000 --> 01:30:39,155
-That's absurd. Look what you've done.
-All I did was try to stay alive.

762
01:30:39,360 --> 01:30:44,514
-I was just too scared to die.
-Only frightened men are brave.

763
01:30:44,680 --> 01:30:48,355
Men who aren't frightened
are insane. You're only brave...

764
01:30:48,560 --> 01:30:53,554
...when there's something
to lose and you still try.

765
01:30:53,800 --> 01:30:55,518
When we get back...

766
01:30:55,720 --> 01:30:58,712
...go to her, hold her...

767
01:30:58,920 --> 01:31:00,512
...and never let go.

768
01:31:00,720 --> 01:31:03,518
That's what I'll do
when I see Margaret.

769
01:31:06,800 --> 01:31:09,314
Tell me more. What's her name?

770
01:31:09,520 --> 01:31:13,354
Margaret.
God, I love that name, don't you?

771
01:31:13,680 --> 01:31:14,669
Yeah.

772
01:31:14,880 --> 01:31:18,190
How do I tell you about her?

773
01:31:18,400 --> 01:31:23,428
If there's such a thing as one woman
for you, it's Margaret for me.

774
01:31:23,680 --> 01:31:28,356
I know it sounds like something
out of <i>Mother Goose</i>, but it's true.

775
01:31:28,600 --> 01:31:32,957
We have a daughter, Sarah.
She looks like her mother...

776
01:31:33,200 --> 01:31:36,954
...which is reason enough
to think she's beautiful.

777
01:31:37,200 --> 01:31:39,316
This is Margaret.

778
01:31:44,160 --> 01:31:47,311
-She's lovely, isn't she?
-Yeah.

779
01:32:02,280 --> 01:32:05,909
She says there's a bridge
eight kilometres from here.

780
01:32:06,120 --> 01:32:08,759
A resistance group is waiting for us.

781
01:32:16,160 --> 01:32:18,116
Come on, old man!

782
01:32:18,320 --> 01:32:20,311
Eat something.

783
01:32:22,800 --> 01:32:25,712
-Here's your watch.
-Thanks.

784
01:32:31,000 --> 01:32:35,312
Son of a bitch! The girl's father
must have called the Germans!

785
01:33:34,880 --> 01:33:36,518
Perfect!

786
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:53,911
Will you come on!

787
01:35:03,800 --> 01:35:06,837
I think I left
my kidneys back there.

788
01:35:07,080 --> 01:35:09,116
You still got your ass.

789
01:36:21,080 --> 01:36:24,709
-I can't go back!
-I'm too scared to argue! Come on!

790
01:36:24,960 --> 01:36:27,349
You're gonna
get us both killed.

791
01:36:27,600 --> 01:36:29,636
When you get
back to London...

792
01:36:29,880 --> 01:36:34,556
...please, look up my wife.
Her name's Margaret. Please.

793
01:36:34,800 --> 01:36:37,314
Tell her I died a brave man.

794
01:36:37,560 --> 01:36:40,472
Tell her yourself!

795
01:37:17,080 --> 01:37:20,390
I get the wet coat again.

796
01:37:22,720 --> 01:37:26,474
No. This time you get the girl.

797
01:37:30,000 --> 01:37:33,754
No, you don't. Not now.

798
01:37:34,000 --> 01:37:36,514
You die on me, I'll kill you.

799
01:37:42,160 --> 01:37:45,152
Want to play cards?
I feel like demolishing you.

800
01:37:45,320 --> 01:37:48,869
You're trying to be cheerful,
you're worried about Daddy.

801
01:37:49,040 --> 01:37:51,315
He's going to be all right.

802
01:37:53,560 --> 01:37:57,712
I love you more than it's
possible to love anyone, you know.

803
01:38:02,800 --> 01:38:05,917
Hello?
Yes.

804
01:38:08,360 --> 01:38:12,876
Mummy, is it good crying
or bad crying?

805
01:38:13,080 --> 01:38:15,310
I knew it.

806
01:38:17,600 --> 01:38:23,709
-Capt. Sellinger, which ward is he in?
-442, just down the corridor.

807
01:38:51,760 --> 01:38:54,320
Hello, old friend.

808
01:38:56,360 --> 01:39:00,319
It's so unfair for anybody's
eyes to be that colour.

809
01:39:01,280 --> 01:39:02,759
I try.

810
01:39:04,560 --> 01:39:06,312
Me too.

811
01:39:10,600 --> 01:39:15,913
-Are you all right? Are you hurt?
-I was lost, but I think I'm back.

812
01:39:17,240 --> 01:39:20,038
I just wish your eyes
weren't that colour.

813
01:39:22,200 --> 01:39:25,033
There's a man in a
room down there...

814
01:39:25,280 --> 01:39:26,952
...a good man...

815
01:39:27,200 --> 01:39:29,316
...I wish he wasn't.

816
01:39:30,080 --> 01:39:35,757
When I heard you'd been shot down
together, it felt like punishment.

817
01:39:36,000 --> 01:39:38,514
Then, after a while...

818
01:39:40,560 --> 01:39:45,315
...I knew that you'd take care of him,
and you would come back.

819
01:39:46,200 --> 01:39:52,799
I love you enough to let you go, which
is more than I've ever loved anybody.

820
01:39:53,000 --> 01:39:56,709
I wish I didn't cry
all the damn time.

821
01:39:58,880 --> 01:40:02,919
I will never care for anyone
the way I care for you.

822
01:40:05,320 --> 01:40:08,517
And to think it had to
work out this way.

823
01:40:08,760 --> 01:40:11,718
Things work out the way
they're supposed to.

824
01:40:12,280 --> 01:40:17,673
And listen. You've got to go to
him and I've got to walk away.

825
01:40:18,200 --> 01:40:21,988
That's what we have to do.
You know that and I know that.

826
01:40:22,520 --> 01:40:26,832
I'm entirely capable of messing
this up, so you must help me.

827
01:40:27,480 --> 01:40:30,711
-I love you, Halloran.
-I love you, Maggie.

828
01:40:33,120 --> 01:40:35,714
Think of me when you drink tea.

